        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Equivalency of input parameters acceptance criteria",
        "description": "FEA model geometry derived directly from the same CAD files used to manufacture the tested constructs. Material properties measured from companion coupons from the same production lot. Contact conditions in the model replicate the physical fixture constraints documented in the test protocol."
      },
      "rationale": "Direct traceability established between physical test specimens and FEA model inputs. CAD-to-mesh pipeline documented; no simplifications introduced that would alter load path. Material coupon data from same production lot used for both test specimen characterization and model input. Required level 3 (full input traceability with documented equivalency mapping) achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Validation metric E/uval computed per ASME V&V 40 Eq. 1 for all three QoIs. Acceptance criterion: E/uval < 1.96 (95% confidence). All three QoIs pass: stiffness E/uval=0.84, yield force E/uval=1.12, force-at-40mm E/uval=0.67. Percentage differences: 3.1%, 4.8%, 2.9% respectively, all below 10% threshold."
      },
      "rationale": "Formal validation metric computed per ASME V&V 40 methodology. All three QoIs satisfy both the E/uval < 1.96 criterion and the <10% absolute difference criterion. Uncertainty budget includes model parameter uncertainty, experimental measurement uncertainty, and inter-laboratory variability. Achieved level 4 (formal uncertainty-aware comparison with multiple QoIs all passing) exceeds required level 3."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-relevance-qoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-relevance-qoi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in the regulatory submission and directly correspond to the clinical performance requirements for pedicle screw constructs under ASTM F1717. Each QoI is directly measured in the bench test and directly predicted by the FEA model."
      },
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary performance metrics in the regulatory submission and are directly specified in ASTM F1717. There is a direct one-to-one mapping between predicted and measured QoIs with no surrogate or proxy quantities. Required level 3 (QoIs directly relevant to COU decision and directly measurable) achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-relevance-val-activities",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The factor 'Relevance of the validation activities to the COU' as defined in ASME V&V 40 Table 1 is intended to assess the degree to which validation activities were conducted in a domain separate from the COU and must be extrapolated — for example, validating a cardiovascular flow model using in-vitro bench data when the COU is in-vivo hemodynamics. In the present case, the validation activity IS the COU: the FEA model is being validated against ASTM F1717 bench testing under exactly the same loading configuration, geometry, and material system that constitutes the intended use. There is no extrapolation gap between validation domain and deployment domain. Assigning a relevance score to an activity that is definitionally identical to the COU would be circular and is therefore not applicable per ASME V&V 40 Section 4.3 guidance on factor applicability."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "rationale": "The FEA model ensemble for non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw compression-bending satisfies all applicable V&V 40 credibility requirements at or above required levels, with the single exception of Test conditions (achieved level 2 vs. required level 3). Eleven of thirteen factors are assessed; two (Numerical solver error; Relevance of the validation activities to the COU) are not-applicable with documented rationales. All three primary QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) pass the formal ASME V&V 40 validation metric (E/uval < 1.96) and the <10% absolute difference criterion. The offset rationale for the Test conditions shortfall is documented below. The overall credibility evidence is judged sufficient to support a Medium assurance level decision for a Class II device with medium model influence and medium decision consequence.",
    "hasOffsetRationale": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/offset/nagaraja-test-conditions",
      "type": "OffsetRationale",
      "name": "Offset rationale for Test conditions shortfall",
      "refersToFactor": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-test-conditions",
      "justification": "The Test conditions factor achieved level 2 against a required level 3 because ASTM F1717 specifies only a single standardized 10-degree compression-bending configuration and no additional loading angle or rate variations were performed. This shortfall is offset by three compensating strengths: (1) the single ASTM F1717 condition is the regulatory gold-standard test configuration and is directly representative of the worst-case clinical loading scenario identified in the device risk analysis; (2) the Output comparison factor achieved level 4 (exceeding its required level 3), demonstrating that the model predictions are robustly validated under the condition that does apply; and (3) the Model inputs factor includes a Monte Carlo sensitivity analysis confirming that QoI predictions are insensitive to loading angle variations of ±2 degrees around the nominal 10-degree configuration (< 1.5% QoI change). The combination of regulatory adequacy of the single test condition, strong output comparison performance, and demonstrated insensitivity to loading angle perturbations provides sufficient compensating evidence to accept the package at Medium assurance level despite the Test conditions shortfall."
    }
  },
